.\r\n\r\nIntroduction\r\n1. The study does not have an introduction.\r\n2. Because there was no introduction, there was also no background for the study. What is the theoretical foundation / paradigm of the study? Are there limitations? Have there been any similar studies? Are there underlying assumptions?\r\n\r\nMethodology\r\n3. The method part (page 2 lines 1-19) is limited to the procedure. There was no discussion/mention of the research design (interpretative phenomenological analysis). This has to be thoroughly described as to why it is to be used and how it will be used.\r\n4. The method part does not mention how the participants were selected. Were they randomly selected from a short-list (considering the inclusion parameters) or were they assigned by the jail management?\r\n5. How were the interview notes and results validated to increase the rigor of the design? Did you ask the respondents to read the transcripts?\r\n\r\nResults and Discussion\r\n6. A few local terms were not defined (e.g. Budol-budol gang page 2 line 27, amin-laya page 5 line 40).\r\n7. Page 2 line 27: Shouldn\'t it be \"possession of illegal drugs\" instead of simply \"drugs\" for the column on case?\r\n8. Formatting of the headings and sub-headings is confusing. Tabs are not aligned consistently.\r\n9. Check the spelling of some Filipino words in the quotations.\r\n10. Page 7 line 35, page 8 line 30: Who is Bles? Is she one of the respondents? Why is she not included in the list of respondents?\r\n11. The emerging paradigm (page 8 line 33) was not thoroughly discussed. Since this is an attempt to illustrate the relation of the themes and sub-themes to each other, there must a clear and comprehensive discussion of how one theme is related to the other. Lines connecting these themes and sub-themes also seem to have been neglected in the discussion. It appears that the paragraphs that followed the paradigm are but reiteration of what was previously mentioned from the results.\r\n\r\nALSO, 